---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Child Custody Modification in Maryland | Material Change in Circumstances | Child Custody with a Plan"
  description="Maryland child custody modification attorneys. When circumstances change significantly, your custody order can be modified. Learn your rights. Call (301) 289-8917 for a free consultation."
  ogTitle="Maryland Child Custody Modification | Child Custody with a Plan"
  ogDescription="Has your situation changed since your custody order? Maryland courts can modify custody based on a material change in circumstances. Our attorneys can help."
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative bg-[#0D6E6E] text-white py-20 md:py-28">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 opacity-10 bg-[url('/grid.svg')] bg-repeat"></div>
    <div class="relative max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <p class="text-[#D4A843] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-sm mb-3">Post-Divorce Custody</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold leading-tight mb-5">
        Child Custody<br class="hidden md:block" /> Modification in Maryland
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-white/80 max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-8">
        Life changes. When it does, your custody order may need to change too. We help Maryland parents navigate the modification process — protecting the best interests of their children every step of the way.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-center">
        <a href="/free-consultation" class="bg-[#D4A843] text-white font-bold px-8 py-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-[#b8902f] transition-colors">
          Book Free Consultation
        </a>
        <a href="tel:3012898917" class="border-2 border-white text-white font-bold px-8 py-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-white hover:text-[#0D6E6E] transition-colors">
          (301) 289-8917
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <div class="bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 py-3">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-500">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-[#0D6E6E]">Home</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/child-custody" class="hover:text-[#0D6E6E]">Child Custody</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-gray-800 font-medium">Custody Modification</span>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start">
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-5">When Can a Custody Order Be Modified?</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
            Maryland courts recognize that circumstances change — children grow, parents relocate, careers shift, and family dynamics evolve. A custody order that made sense at the time of your divorce may no longer serve your children's best interests today.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
            To successfully modify a custody order in Maryland, you must demonstrate two things:
          </p>
          <div class="space-y-4 mb-4">
            <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 bg-[#0D6E6E] text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm flex-shrink-0">1</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold text-gray-900">Material Change in Circumstances</p>
                <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">A significant change has occurred since the last custody order was entered. The change must be substantial — not minor or temporary.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 bg-[#0D6E6E] text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm flex-shrink-0">2</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-bold text-gray-900">Best Interests of the Child</p>
                <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">The proposed modification serves the child's best interests better than the current arrangement. This is the court's paramount concern.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="text-gray-600">
            Meeting both standards requires skilled legal advocacy. Our attorneys understand exactly what Maryland courts need to see — and how to present your case effectively.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-[#D4A843]/30 rounded-xl p-6">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">⚠️ Do NOT Informally Modify Custody</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Many parents make informal changes to their custody arrangements without court approval — this can seriously harm your legal position. An existing court order remains enforceable until modified by another court order. Always formalize changes through proper legal channels.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[#0D6E6E]/5 border border-[#0D6E6E]/20 rounded-xl p-5">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">How Long Does Modification Take?</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-2">Timeline depends on complexity and whether the other parent contests the modification:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-600">
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#D4A843]">•</span>Uncontested modification: 30–90 days</li>
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#D4A843]">•</span>Contested modification: 6–18 months</li>
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#D4A843]">•</span>Emergency modification: Days (if safety is at stake)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Material Change Examples -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-gray-50">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 text-center mb-3">What Qualifies as a "Material Change"?</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-center mb-12 max-w-2xl mx-auto">Maryland courts take modification requests seriously. Here are the most commonly recognized material changes that can support a modification petition.</p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        {[
          {
            icon: "📦",
            title: "Relocation",
            desc: "One parent plans to move a significant distance away — especially out of state — which makes the current parenting schedule impractical or impossible."
          },
          {
            icon: "💍",
            title: "Remarriage",
            desc: "A parent remarries and introduces a new partner or step-parent into the child's household, significantly altering the home environment."
          },
          {
            icon: "💼",
            title: "Major Employment Change",
            desc: "A parent gains or loses employment, changes work hours dramatically, or must travel frequently — affecting their availability for parenting time."
          },
          {
            icon: "⚠️",
            title: "Safety Concerns",
            desc: "Evidence of domestic violence, child abuse, neglect, substance abuse, or criminal conduct that puts the child's wellbeing at risk."
          },
          {
            icon: "🧒",
            title: "Child's Changing Needs",
            desc: "A child's evolving needs — educational, medical, emotional, or developmental — are no longer adequately met by the current arrangement."
          },
          {
            icon: "🎓",
            title: "School & Education",
            desc: "Changes in school districts, educational needs, or academic performance issues that require a different residential arrangement."
          },
          {
            icon: "🏥",
            title: "Serious Illness or Disability",
            desc: "A parent or child develops a serious health condition that significantly affects their ability to function under the current custody arrangement."
          },
          {
            icon: "🗣️",
            title: "Child's Preference",
            desc: "Older children (typically 12+) who express a clear, reasoned preference for a different living arrangement — courts give this increasing weight with age."
          },
          {
            icon: "🚫",
            title: "Parental Interference",
            desc: "Persistent violation of the custody order, parental alienation, or deliberate interference with the other parent's relationship with the child."
          }
        ].map(change => (
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
            <div class="text-3xl mb-3">{change.icon}</div>
            <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">{change.title}</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">{change.desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Process -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 text-center mb-3">The Modification Process in Maryland</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-center mb-12 max-w-2xl mx-auto">Here's how the custody modification process typically unfolds in Maryland family court.</p>
      <div class="relative">
        <div class="absolute left-8 top-0 bottom-0 w-0.5 bg-[#0D6E6E]/20 hidden md:block"></div>
        <div class="space-y-8">
          {[
            {
              step: "01",
              title: "Consultation & Case Evaluation",
              desc: "We review your current custody order, the changes that have occurred, and assess whether you have sufficient grounds for a modification petition. We explain your realistic options and likely outcomes."
            },
            {
              step: "02",
              title: "Filing the Petition",
              desc: "We file a Petition for Modification of Custody in the appropriate Maryland circuit court. The petition must clearly state the material change in circumstances and the proposed new custody arrangement."
            },
            {
              step: "03",
              title: "Service & Response",
              desc: "The other parent is served with the petition and has the opportunity to respond. They may consent to the modification or file a counter-petition with their own proposed arrangement."
            },
            {
              step: "04",
              title: "Discovery & Evidence Gathering",
              desc: "In contested cases, both parties may conduct discovery — exchanging documents, taking depositions, and gathering evidence to support their respective positions."
            },
            {
              step: "05",
              title: "Mediation (Often Required)",
              desc: "Many Maryland courts require parties to attempt mediation before a hearing. Our attorneys prepare you thoroughly for mediation and advocate for your position throughout the process."
            },
            {
              step: "06",
              title: "Hearing or Trial",
              desc: "If no agreement is reached, the court holds a hearing where both parties present evidence. The judge applies the best-interests standard and issues a new custody order."
            }
          ].map((step, i) => (
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start">
              <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-[#0D6E6E] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 z-10">
                <span class="text-[#D4A843] font-bold">{step.step}</span>
              </div>
              <div class="flex-1 bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-100">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">{step.title}</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">{step.desc}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Emergency -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-[#0D6E6E]">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
        <div class="text-white">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-5">Emergency Custody Modification</h2>
          <p class="text-white/80 mb-4">
            When a child's immediate safety is at risk, waiting months for a regular modification hearing is not an option. Maryland courts can issue emergency custody modifications — sometimes within days — when there is credible evidence of imminent harm.
          </p>
          <p class="text-white/80 mb-5">
            If you believe your child is in immediate danger, contact us right away. We move quickly to file emergency petitions and obtain protective orders.
          </p>
          <div class="space-y-2">
            {[
              "Domestic violence or physical abuse",
              "Child sexual abuse allegations",
              "Substance abuse in the home",
              "Kidnapping or flight risk",
              "Severe parental neglect",
              "Mental health crisis endangering the child"
            ].map(item => (
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-white/90 text-sm">
                <span class="text-[#D4A843] font-bold">⚠</span>
                {item}
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Call Us Now If Your Child is at Risk</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-5 text-sm">Our Maryland child custody attorneys understand the urgency of emergency situations. We're available to discuss emergency modifications and protective orders.</p>
          <a href="tel:3012898917" class="block text-center bg-[#0D6E6E] text-white font-bold px-6 py-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-[#0a5a5a] transition-colors text-lg">
            Call (301) 289-8917
          </a>
          <p class="text-center text-xs text-gray-500 mt-3">Mon–Fri 9AM–9PM · Rockville & Baltimore offices</p>
          <div class="mt-5 border-t border-gray-100 pt-5">
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">If there is immediate physical danger, contact 911 or law enforcement first, then reach out to our office.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Both Sides -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-gray-50">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 text-center mb-12">We Represent Both Petitioners and Respondents</h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[#0D6E6E] mb-4">Seeking a Modification?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Whether you need more parenting time, a different custody structure, or emergency protection, we help you build a compelling petition backed by evidence that meets Maryland's legal standard.</p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
            {[
              "Identify and document the material change",
              "Frame your petition to maximize success",
              "Gather supporting evidence and witnesses",
              "Prepare you for mediation and hearings",
              "Advocate for your preferred parenting arrangement"
            ].map(item => (
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[#D4A843] font-bold">✓</span>
                {item}
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-[#0D6E6E] mb-4">Opposing a Modification?</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">If your co-parent is seeking to change a custody arrangement you believe is working well for your children, we defend your position and challenge whether a genuine material change has occurred.</p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
            {[
              "Challenge whether a genuine material change exists",
              "Present evidence that current order serves children's best interests",
              "Counter the other parent's proposed modifications",
              "Expose improper motives behind modification attempts",
              "Protect your parental rights and relationship with your child"
            ].map(item => (
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[#D4A843] font-bold">✓</span>
                {item}
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Has Your Situation Changed?</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">If circumstances have significantly shifted since your custody order was entered, you may be entitled to a modification. Speak with a Maryland child custody attorney today — free of charge.</p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-center">
        <a href="/free-consultation" class="bg-[#0D6E6E] text-white font-bold px-8 py-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-[#0a5a5a] transition-colors">
          Book Free Consultation
        </a>
        <a href="tel:3012898917" class="bg-[#D4A843] text-white font-bold px-8 py-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-[#b8902f] transition-colors">
          Call (301) 289-8917
        </a>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-4">Rockville: 100 Park Ave Suite 205 · Baltimore: 1537 Light St #100 · Mon–Fri 9AM–9PM</p>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
